	   <tr><td colspan=2>You are only partially right, sai were developed from farm tools but it was a tool used in planting seed not a hay fork.&nbsp;&nbsp;They are not strictly blocking and disarming weapons they are also used to strike primarily as blunt weapons.  My knowledge comes from the fact that I have studied Kobujitsu (Okinawan weapons)for a little over 10 years, and it is the style that all Japanese forms using nunchaku, sai, tonfa and kamas are based on.  It also uses the cane, oar kusari-gama, manriki, manriki-gusari, and several other more obscure Japanese weapons.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
